WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.050 --> 00:00:02.299
MALE SPEAKER: A few weeks
ago, I went to a comedy show

00:00:02.299 --> 00:00:04.759
in the city, and I got
talking to this Irish guy who

00:00:04.759 --> 00:00:06.300
had this very
interesting background.

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:09.350
He had this debilitating
fear of public speaking.

00:00:09.350 --> 00:00:13.370
So the obvious way to
approach conquering that fear

00:00:13.370 --> 00:00:17.390
is, of course, becoming
a stand-up comedian.

00:00:17.390 --> 00:00:19.560
So as a non-comedian,
he pretended

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:22.040
to be a stand-up comedian
for a year to get over

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:25.020
his fear of public speaking.

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:26.400
An interesting
way to attack it--

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:28.370
but in the process of
doing that, he learned

00:00:28.370 --> 00:00:31.050
a lot about comedy techniques,
about stand-up techniques,

00:00:31.050 --> 00:00:33.090
and about public
speaking in general.

00:00:33.090 --> 00:00:35.189
And he took all
these ideas, and he

00:00:35.189 --> 00:00:37.730
thought about how to make more
effective presentations, which

00:00:37.730 --> 00:00:40.350
we had a long discussion
about because I care deeply

00:00:40.350 --> 00:00:41.950
about public
presentations and humor

00:00:41.950 --> 00:00:44.520
and how to make them
all more engaging.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:45.730
And he took that information.

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:47.424
He wrapped it up
to it into a book.

00:00:47.424 --> 00:00:49.840
And I thought, well, that
sounds like an interesting book.

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:51.226
I'd like to read it someday.

00:00:51.226 --> 00:00:54.320
So three days later, there was
an internal email at Google

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:56.560
that said, hey, there's
this author named

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:01.150
David Nihill who has a new book
coming out on public speaking.

00:01:01.150 --> 00:01:03.020
Would anybody like to host this?

00:01:03.020 --> 00:01:05.459
Well, that's a perfect
opportunity for me

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:08.530
to have an excuse to
actually read his book now.

00:01:08.530 --> 00:01:11.500
So here we are, a
few weeks later.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:13.420
And he's going to
tell us about how

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:16.720
to make more effective
presentations using techniques

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:18.240
of stand-up comedians.

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:23.470
I think we all know and suffer
from public presentations that

00:01:23.470 --> 00:01:26.900
could be a heck of a lot more
entertaining than they are.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:29.050
And there's no reason why
they shouldn't be, except

00:01:29.050 --> 00:01:31.440
that maybe people don't
common techniques that

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:33.092
could be used to make them so.

00:01:33.092 --> 00:01:34.800
So that's sort of what
the book is about,

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:36.910
and it's about what the
presentation is about.

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:39.490
And please welcome David Nihill.

00:01:39.490 --> 00:01:42.470
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:42.470 --> 00:01:43.780
DAVID NIHILL: Thank you.

00:01:43.780 --> 00:01:45.780
Fine introduction.

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:47.920
So I know that sounds
like the worst plan ever.

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:49.310
You're scared of
public speaking,

00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:52.160
and you're going to pretend
to be a comedian for a year?

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:54.760
That does not sound
like a good idea.

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:57.830
It 100% was not a good idea.

00:01:57.830 --> 00:02:00.170
But at least we've written
it down at this stage.

00:02:00.170 --> 00:02:00.920
Thanks for coming.

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:03.970
I always like to ask
who thinks they're not

00:02:03.970 --> 00:02:05.610
funny by a show of hands.

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:08.729
So is there anyone who's
like, I'm not funny at all?

00:02:08.729 --> 00:02:11.590
So four of you are not
funny, and the rest of you

00:02:11.590 --> 00:02:13.800
are really, really funny?

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:16.060
So this will be fine
no matter what I say.

00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:19.010
Because we can just call upon
you guys to rock it, right?

00:02:19.010 --> 00:02:20.630
Anyone else hate
public speaking?

00:02:20.630 --> 00:02:22.730
I totally hate public
speaking, which is ironic

00:02:22.730 --> 00:02:24.600
that I'm merely
laying an egg on video

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:26.500
right now here
recording this one.

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:27.000
How many?

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:28.380
Keep the hands up.

00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:31.830
I mean like shaking the page
kind of fear public speaking?

00:02:31.830 --> 00:02:35.310
That was me, always.

00:02:35.310 --> 00:02:37.070
Nobody over here
in the States knew.

00:02:37.070 --> 00:02:39.760
Obviously I'm from Ireland
originally with a dodgy accent,

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:41.580
and I went to
university in Ireland.

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:44.299
And all my friends had me
nicknamed shakin' Stevens,

00:02:44.299 --> 00:02:45.840
because whenever I
had a bit of paper

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:47.820
in my hand for a
presentation, public speaking,

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:50.570
it would just start moving
around like this all the time,

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:51.630
and I'd start sweating.

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:53.780
And do you know this
feeling at all, anybody?

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:55.120
And it's just getting worse.

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:56.911
And I'm holding the
microphone, and I can't

00:02:56.911 --> 00:03:00.370
hold it steady anymore either.

00:03:00.370 --> 00:03:02.650
It was always, always,
always that bad for me.

00:03:02.650 --> 00:03:05.140
And honestly, I would
have described it

00:03:05.140 --> 00:03:06.360
as a crippling fear.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:08.960
If you ask me, in any way
public speaking for you,

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:10.570
it is a crippling fear.

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:13.530
And that was until a rather
serious phone call that I

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:15.287
got about a friend of mine.

00:03:15.287 --> 00:03:16.870
And it was to inform
me that he'd just

00:03:16.870 --> 00:03:19.880
suffered a severe
spinal cord injury,

00:03:19.880 --> 00:03:21.640
and he might never walk again.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:24.130
And his insurance
provider cut him off,

00:03:24.130 --> 00:03:26.480
and we were trying to come
up with ways, because he

00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:28.500
was in no way accepting
this that he was never

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:29.333
going to walk again.

00:03:29.333 --> 00:03:31.480
He's like, I'm going
to get back on my feet.

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:33.830
I just need to be able to do
the rehab process to do it.

00:03:33.830 --> 00:03:36.038
So we're like, well, as his
friends, we got together.

00:03:36.038 --> 00:03:37.920
We're like, let's
start doing fundraisers

00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:39.270
to get him back on his feet.

00:03:39.270 --> 00:03:41.580
And I just happened to
live next to this guy who

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:44.460
was a touring comedian
and a headlining comedian.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:46.710
And I was like, hey,
Tim, would you by chance

00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:48.910
do this comedy show
fundraiser we're going to do?

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:50.570
I don't know anything about
organizing it or anything,

00:03:50.570 --> 00:03:51.660
but let's do it.

00:03:51.660 --> 00:03:52.832
And he said yes.

00:03:52.832 --> 00:03:54.290
And all my friends
were like, well,

00:03:54.290 --> 00:03:55.940
you're naturally
pretty talkative, you

00:03:55.940 --> 00:03:58.231
are going to be the host
because you are organizing it.

00:03:58.231 --> 00:04:01.794
And I was like, I am not hosting
that never, absolutely no way.

00:04:01.794 --> 00:04:03.210
And they were all
just kept at me.

00:04:03.210 --> 00:04:04.630
No, no, you have to.

00:04:04.630 --> 00:04:07.430
And up to that moment, I
was like there's no way.

00:04:07.430 --> 00:04:11.420
I can describe this as
a fear that's crippling.

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:13.510
I mean, faced with a
more serious impact--

00:04:13.510 --> 00:04:16.269
the real impact of that
word, I was like, all right,

00:04:16.269 --> 00:04:17.579
time to get over this.

00:04:17.579 --> 00:04:19.634
So I went, and I did this.

00:04:19.634 --> 00:04:21.050
And I was looking
right-- if I had

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:22.850
to get good at public
speaking quickly

00:04:22.850 --> 00:04:24.558
and had to get over
this fear, like who's

00:04:24.558 --> 00:04:25.820
the best person to study?

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:27.570
Like, where do I get
the information from?

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:28.470
There's books out there.

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:29.720
I don't want to read them all.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:30.950
I don't really have time.

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:31.910
Where do I get it from?

00:04:31.910 --> 00:04:33.080
Who are the true masters?

00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:34.570
So I was thinking,
well, comedians

00:04:34.570 --> 00:04:36.620
are probably the true
masters of public speaking.

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:38.514
I just read a lot of
Malcolm Gladwell, which

00:04:38.514 --> 00:04:39.930
I'm sure you're
very familiar with

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:42.330
and his 10,000 hour rule
that makes a master.

00:04:42.330 --> 00:04:44.850
Well, comedians are on stage
more than anybody else.

00:04:44.850 --> 00:04:46.720
They take people to
a range of emotions

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.309
more so than anybody else.

00:04:48.309 --> 00:04:49.600
Let me see what I can get from.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.547
It's a comedy show anyway.

00:04:51.547 --> 00:04:53.130
So it'll be pretty
useful, and I don't

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:55.570
want to be that one funny
nervous guy with the shakin'

00:04:55.570 --> 00:04:58.542
Stevens moves and
see what happens.

00:04:58.542 --> 00:04:59.500
So it went really well.

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:01.750
We raised a good chunk
of money, totally packed.

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:05.264
And it went so well that the
main comedian asked me, like,

00:05:05.264 --> 00:05:06.680
literally, like,
hey, Dave, do you

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:08.890
want to open for me at
the Punchline Comedy

00:05:08.890 --> 00:05:10.010
Club in a couple of weeks?

00:05:10.010 --> 00:05:13.680
And I was like, do I tell him
that I haven't got a clue?

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:15.160
I was like, nah.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:17.270
Yeah, sure, I'll do that.

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:17.970
So I did it.

00:05:17.970 --> 00:05:19.962
And I'd just been
reading-- he's an author.

00:05:19.962 --> 00:05:21.670
I'm sure he's been
here at Google before.

00:05:21.670 --> 00:05:23.720
You might be familiar
with his work, AJ Jacobs.

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:26.240
He's very much referenced
by in Tim Ferriss's books.

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:28.810
He was known for going deep
into a topic for a year

00:05:28.810 --> 00:05:30.060
and writing about it.

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:31.125
And I read his books.

00:05:31.125 --> 00:05:33.250
And he'd just done "The
Year of Living Biblically,"

00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:36.830
where even though he was Jewish,
followed the rules of the Bible

00:05:36.830 --> 00:05:39.010
to the letter of the law,
like so much so he was out

00:05:39.010 --> 00:05:41.400
throwing stones at adulterers.

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:42.660
It was pretty cool.

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:44.967
I was like, right.

00:05:44.967 --> 00:05:46.550
Maybe I'll keep this
going for a year.

00:05:46.550 --> 00:05:47.940
Maybe I'll get
Tim Ferriss on it.

00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:50.240
I was very influenced by
him breaking things down,

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:52.010
80/20 principle,
trying to figure out

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:54.010
what are the techniques
that are most effective.

00:05:54.010 --> 00:05:55.350
And I'll do it for a full year.

00:05:55.350 --> 00:05:57.380
And I was like, well, I've
just left a corporate job.

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:58.880
And if I tell my
friends I'm going

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:01.230
to put all my effort into
being a comedian for a year

00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:04.480
with actually no objective of
being a full time comedian,

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:07.300
and very little potential income
from this choice for a year,

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:09.076
they're going to
think I am bonkers.

00:06:09.076 --> 00:06:10.950
So I was like, I better
make up a stage name,

00:06:10.950 --> 00:06:13.110
because I don't want people
tagging me on Facebook doing

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:15.151
all this comedy stuff,
and I hate public speaking

00:06:15.151 --> 00:06:16.390
in the first place.

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:18.060
So I got a bit carried away.

00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:20.500
And we came up with Irish Dave.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:21.450
That was the comedian.

00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:23.080
And this kind of
became the book,

00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:24.580
was my learning along the way.

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:27.610
But here I got very much
carried away with this.

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:30.420
Irish Dave doesn't sound like
the most novel stage name

00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:32.240
to an Irish person,
but Americans seem

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:34.620
to like it for some reason.

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:36.330
And I went as an
accomplished comedian.

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:38.455
So I was trying to make it
known that I was already

00:06:38.455 --> 00:06:39.880
well-versed in
comedy because it's

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:43.190
much easier to get booked in
clubs and festivals that way.

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:44.740
So this was one
of the first shows

00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:46.690
I managed to get booked
on, a real highlight.

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:50.850
You can see "Estrogen Entree
with a Side of Balls."

00:06:50.850 --> 00:06:53.590
I got to be that side of balls.

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:55.030
As you can see
with all the ladies

00:06:55.030 --> 00:06:57.320
names, a real proud
moment for my parents.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:06:58.980
I can imagine--
David, glad to see

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:00.390
you've left your corporate job.

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:02.580
When are you going back
to it again, please?

00:07:02.580 --> 00:07:04.610
[INAUDIBLE] side of balls.

00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:07.020
Loads and loads of festivals,
loads of comedy clubs

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:08.070
all over the US.

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:10.010
And it wasn't all totally nutty.

00:07:10.010 --> 00:07:11.899
I learned a lot along the way.

00:07:11.899 --> 00:07:13.690
And some of the cooler
ones, are any of you

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:17.160
familiar with NPR's The Moth,
the storytelling series--

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:18.690
true stories told live?

00:07:18.690 --> 00:07:21.090
So I was trying to get on
any stage that would have me.

00:07:21.090 --> 00:07:23.070
So I went along, told
a story, and I won.

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:24.570
And then they're
like, well, now you

00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:26.278
have to go on our
biggest event that they

00:07:26.278 --> 00:07:28.550
produce worldwide
is in San Francisco,

00:07:28.550 --> 00:07:29.820
in the Castro Theatre.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:32.320
So that little ant
on stage is me.

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:34.100
And it's 1,400
people there, and I

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:36.860
am about to lay an
egg I am so nervous.

00:07:36.860 --> 00:07:38.520
And if you shook
my hand beforehand,

00:07:38.520 --> 00:07:40.020
you'd feel like
you'd been assaulted

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:43.760
by a semi-defrosted
mackerel-- like, bad.

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:44.590
I was so nervous.

00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:46.450
But you wouldn't know it if
you were in the audience.

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:47.960
So over a year of
experiments, I'd

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:49.585
learned enough to
make it at least look

00:07:49.585 --> 00:07:52.230
like I was quite comfortable
where I very much was not

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:53.100
on stage.

00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:54.870
And telling that
story that night,

00:07:54.870 --> 00:07:57.340
I could never have predicted
what would have happened.

00:07:57.340 --> 00:07:59.626
It set off a lot of
really cool stuff

00:07:59.626 --> 00:08:02.000
that I'm going to tell you
about by the end of this talk.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.370
So I just want to
give you an overview

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:05.828
some of the things in the book
that I learned along the way

00:08:05.828 --> 00:08:07.800
that I think you can
replicate, and in the end

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:09.540
we'll get some questions
going because I

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:10.520
know there's loads around it.

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:12.890
But I just wanted to focus on
what were the techniques that I

00:08:12.890 --> 00:08:14.380
was using to do
this along the way

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:16.210
and what I saw from comedians.

00:08:16.210 --> 00:08:18.710
Because everyone I saw
along the way in comedy,

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:20.800
they didn't all get
famous as comedians.

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:22.750
In fact, very few of them did.

00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:26.310
But every single one of them
got funnier along the way.

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:29.780
They were very much showing that
there was a process behind it.

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:31.450
All of their writing got better.

00:08:31.450 --> 00:08:33.240
So there was certain
techniques behind it.

00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:35.480
So if I said to you
you can become funnier,

00:08:35.480 --> 00:08:36.880
you'd be like, well, no.

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:37.395
You're nuts.

00:08:37.395 --> 00:08:39.270
Or most of you today
would be like, yeah, I'm

00:08:39.270 --> 00:08:40.960
funny enough as
it, which is what

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:42.799
I got from the raise of hands.

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:45.517
You're like, no, no no we're
all fine in this department.

00:08:45.517 --> 00:08:47.850
But comedians over time, they
all become better writers.

00:08:47.850 --> 00:08:49.800
So if I said to you you
can become a better writer,

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:50.924
you'd say, well, of course.

00:08:50.924 --> 00:08:52.740
I just need to do a
little bit every day.

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:54.535
And that's effectively
what they did.

00:08:54.535 --> 00:08:55.910
So over the course
of the year, I

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:59.260
guess there was really three
key findings [INAUDIBLE].

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:01.150
So I studied all the
leading TED Talks.

00:09:01.150 --> 00:09:03.170
I studied all the most
popular business talks.

00:09:03.170 --> 00:09:05.730
And we were trying to find
trends for humor in there

00:09:05.730 --> 00:09:07.167
because no one had done it.

00:09:07.167 --> 00:09:08.750
And I was like, well,
surely everybody

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:11.020
says humor is a key part
of talks, but is it?

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:12.550
So sure enough, it was.

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:15.050
All these top speakers
were using humor.

00:09:15.050 --> 00:09:17.700
They were using the exact
same techniques as comedians,

00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:20.620
even though a lot of
them did not know it.

00:09:20.620 --> 00:09:23.400
And the nice thing for only
the four people in here

00:09:23.400 --> 00:09:27.070
that weren't funny, you don't
need to be a natural comedian

