00:37:23.750 --> 00:37:26.090
Has that ever popped
up for anyone?

00:37:26.090 --> 00:37:27.604
I see a lot of head nods.

00:37:27.604 --> 00:37:29.020
I think the single
biggest thing I

00:37:29.020 --> 00:37:32.320
learned in the whole year I
learned from Richard, actually,

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:36.030
our fake Indian President Obama
you had in the video there,

00:37:36.030 --> 00:37:37.310
in the low budget recording.

00:37:37.310 --> 00:37:39.520
But he taught me about something
called the memory palace, which

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:41.978
I hadn't heard of or I wasn't
aware of, but you might have.

00:37:41.978 --> 00:37:43.760
Joshua Foer wrote a
very good book on it

00:37:43.760 --> 00:37:45.650
called "Moonwalking
with Einstein,"

00:37:45.650 --> 00:37:48.000
which essentially is a
way to remember your talk

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:50.010
or anything you need
to remember and never

00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:52.900
worry about forgetting it
in any way, shape, or form.

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:56.040
So do you guys-- you didn't
speak Spanish earlier.

00:37:56.040 --> 00:37:59.419
You remember the word for "to
put" or "to fit," I should say?

00:37:59.419 --> 00:38:00.085
AUDIENCE: Caber.

00:38:00.085 --> 00:38:02.090
DAVID NIHILL: Caber,
nearly everybody,

00:38:02.090 --> 00:38:03.580
pretty much everybody.

00:38:03.580 --> 00:38:06.360
Can't test you guys on the
livestream inside of it.

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:08.332
But you won't forget that story.

00:38:08.332 --> 00:38:09.790
That's just the
way you wrapped it.

00:38:09.790 --> 00:38:11.570
And it even gets more
powerful of a memory

00:38:11.570 --> 00:38:15.280
if you take that story and you
put it in a specific location.

00:38:15.280 --> 00:38:19.690
So if I ask you guys, have you
got a favorite restaurant you

00:38:19.690 --> 00:38:23.370
like in San Francisco or
the Bay Area and picture it,

00:38:23.370 --> 00:38:25.760
and be like, when I walk
in, where's the server?

00:38:25.760 --> 00:38:27.030
How many tables are there?

00:38:27.030 --> 00:38:28.270
Where's the bathroom?

00:38:28.270 --> 00:38:30.145
It's very easy for that
to come to your mind.

00:38:30.145 --> 00:38:32.644
And you're like, oh no, there's
like six tables on the left.

00:38:32.644 --> 00:38:33.830
The server's on the right.

00:38:33.830 --> 00:38:34.870
OK, I get it.

00:38:34.870 --> 00:38:37.930
So if you take a space like
that that you remember easily,

00:38:37.930 --> 00:38:40.060
now make it something
super familiar,

00:38:40.060 --> 00:38:43.340
like your house or your
office, or somewhere

00:38:43.340 --> 00:38:44.620
where you grew up in.

00:38:44.620 --> 00:38:46.840
And you plant all
these little stories

00:38:46.840 --> 00:38:49.240
as memories within
that structure.

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:50.750
All of a sudden,
now you're never

00:38:50.750 --> 00:38:52.710
trying to remember a word.

00:38:52.710 --> 00:38:54.310
You're trying to
remember a location.

00:38:54.310 --> 00:38:55.400
So you're on stage.

00:38:55.400 --> 00:38:57.700
And you're literally like,
where am I in the talk?

00:38:57.700 --> 00:38:58.590
I'm in the kitchen.

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:00.270
Who's in the kitchen?

00:39:00.270 --> 00:39:00.770
OK.

00:39:00.770 --> 00:39:03.240
Those crazy memories I
planted there is a story.

00:39:03.240 --> 00:39:06.350
So if I'm going to talk about,
say, Mexico and economic growth

00:39:06.350 --> 00:39:09.490
and I need to remember
the GDP of Mexico is 11%,

00:39:09.490 --> 00:39:11.510
I'm literally going to
picture a Mexican guy.

00:39:11.510 --> 00:39:12.370
I open my door.

00:39:12.370 --> 00:39:14.210
And there's a guy from
Mexico on a donkey,

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.427
and he's got no
pants on whatsoever.

00:39:16.427 --> 00:39:18.760
And he's a bottle of Guinness
in each hand for no reason

00:39:18.760 --> 00:39:21.220
whatsoever, and he has
a soccer Jersey on him.

00:39:21.220 --> 00:39:23.550
And 11 is the number
on the jersey.

00:39:23.550 --> 00:39:25.800
So the first thing I need
to talk about is in my talk,

00:39:25.800 --> 00:39:26.780
I open the door.

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:29.950
I'm starting to
talk about Mexico.

00:39:29.950 --> 00:39:31.200
I hope I have the image of it.

00:39:31.200 --> 00:39:31.700
Oh yeah.

00:39:31.700 --> 00:39:36.010
So remembered the story I
told you I told for The Moth

00:39:36.010 --> 00:39:37.960
for 1,400 people?

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:39.929
That's all I had
in my back pocket.

00:39:39.929 --> 00:39:41.220
And it stays in my back pocket.

00:39:41.220 --> 00:39:42.470
I never take it out in anyway.

00:39:42.470 --> 00:39:44.594
Because if you have any
notes, people automatically

00:39:44.594 --> 00:39:47.020
assume that you didn't prepare
for this, whether you want

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:48.904
them to get that idea or not.

00:39:48.904 --> 00:39:49.820
And that's all I have.

00:39:49.820 --> 00:39:51.528
And you'll be looking
at thinking, that's

00:39:51.528 --> 00:39:52.750
a bit of a strange story.

00:39:52.750 --> 00:39:53.820
What are those notes?

00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:58.380
Potatoes, 69, cookies,
fireworks, Lululemon pants.

00:39:58.380 --> 00:40:00.730
It was about my mother
coming to San Francisco

00:40:00.730 --> 00:40:02.790
as a conservative
kind Irish lady

00:40:02.790 --> 00:40:05.010
and getting a lot
less conservative

00:40:05.010 --> 00:40:07.400
and going home wearing
like Lululemon pants

00:40:07.400 --> 00:40:10.990
and getting a bit of a taste for
weed cookies, which was pretty

00:40:10.990 --> 00:40:12.960
interesting, to say the least.

00:40:12.960 --> 00:40:15.710
But all I've done is I
positioned a little story

00:40:15.710 --> 00:40:17.681
in every location in my room.

00:40:17.681 --> 00:40:19.930
And the nice thing is when
you're doing your talk now,

00:40:19.930 --> 00:40:22.120
you're not looking at
a list of bullet points

00:40:22.120 --> 00:40:23.740
anymore and trying
to remember them.

00:40:23.740 --> 00:40:25.940
And the really cool thing
is when you do this,

00:40:25.940 --> 00:40:27.700
and you realize, OK, this works.

00:40:27.700 --> 00:40:29.770
I actually can't forget
this stuff anymore.

00:40:29.770 --> 00:40:32.560
Then you can sit in the audience
and watch the three speakers

00:40:32.560 --> 00:40:33.180
before you.

00:40:33.180 --> 00:40:34.410
So have you ever
been to a conference

00:40:34.410 --> 00:40:36.320
or done public speaking
and someone went on

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:38.110
and they talked about
the exact same thing

00:40:38.110 --> 00:40:39.550
that the last guy talked about?

00:40:39.550 --> 00:40:42.022
And you're sitting there
going, why is he saying this?

00:40:42.022 --> 00:40:43.980
Why doesn't he argue with
the last guy's point?

00:40:43.980 --> 00:40:45.410
Or why is he saying
the same thing?

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:46.951
And the answer is
normally because he

00:40:46.951 --> 00:40:49.666
was backstage sweating,
reading off a load of notes.

00:40:49.666 --> 00:40:51.290
And he wasn't totally
confident that he

00:40:51.290 --> 00:40:53.831
was going to remember it, and
the easiest way you'll ever get

00:40:53.831 --> 00:40:56.190
laughs if the really funny
guy goes on before you,

00:40:56.190 --> 00:40:58.224
then you just talk
about how funny he was.

00:40:58.224 --> 00:40:59.890
And you make the same
jokes that he did.

00:40:59.890 --> 00:41:01.720
In comedy, they call
that a call back.

00:41:01.720 --> 00:41:03.730
And you just use something
that already worked.

00:41:03.730 --> 00:41:05.146
But when you know
you're not going

00:41:05.146 --> 00:41:08.240
to get to go blank on stage, the
shaking and the sweating calms

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:10.740
down a lot before you go on,
because you're like, all right,

00:41:10.740 --> 00:41:13.610
the biggest single fear, I've
just taken that off the table.

00:41:13.610 --> 00:41:15.925
And this works 100% of the time.

00:41:15.925 --> 00:41:17.300
I've never gone
blank using this.

00:41:17.300 --> 00:41:18.841
Any of my friends
that have used this

00:41:18.841 --> 00:41:20.320
have never gone blank using it.

00:41:20.320 --> 00:41:23.590
So it's a big topic by itself,
but to be honest, that's it.

00:41:23.590 --> 00:41:25.292
Just draw out a
floor plan and create

00:41:25.292 --> 00:41:26.500
a little memory of something.

00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:28.630
Put it in each place,
and that's your talk.

00:41:28.630 --> 00:41:30.630
And when you get really
good at doing your talk,

00:41:30.630 --> 00:41:32.671
if you've ever spoke at
a conference, some of you

00:41:32.671 --> 00:41:35.036
might relate to this where
it's a 25 minute talk.

00:41:35.036 --> 00:41:36.410
And they're like,
actually-- just

00:41:36.410 --> 00:41:38.570
before you go on-- everybody
else ran over a bit.

00:41:38.570 --> 00:41:40.010
If you can just do 11 minutes.

00:41:40.010 --> 00:41:40.782
That'll be fine.

00:41:40.782 --> 00:41:41.740
You're like 11 minutes!

00:41:41.740 --> 00:41:43.010
I've got like 50 slides.

00:41:43.010 --> 00:41:43.927
What am I going to do?

00:41:43.927 --> 00:41:45.551
When you get really
good at doing this,

00:41:45.551 --> 00:41:48.320
you know how long you're going
to have to spend in each room.

00:41:48.320 --> 00:41:49.810
So I know if I go
into the bathroom

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:51.726
and I'm talking about
the intellectual capital

00:41:51.726 --> 00:41:54.517
of California that is
Stockton, for you guys

00:41:54.517 --> 00:41:56.600
there, that's literally
going to take me a minute.

00:41:56.600 --> 00:41:57.310
So I'm like, all right.

00:41:57.310 --> 00:41:58.490
I'm not going into the bathroom.

00:41:58.490 --> 00:41:59.940
I'm going to walk straight
through the kitchen,

00:41:59.940 --> 00:42:02.270
and that's going to take another
two minutes off the time.

00:42:02.270 --> 00:42:04.395
And all of a sudden, you
become very, very flexible

00:42:04.395 --> 00:42:05.387
with what you're doing.

00:42:05.387 --> 00:42:07.220
So I'd say of all the
tips and the takeaways

00:42:07.220 --> 00:42:10.090
I got for the world of business,
or any form of public speaking,

00:42:10.090 --> 00:42:12.510
this is number one for
me because it allowed

00:42:12.510 --> 00:42:14.280
me to relax quite a lot.

00:42:14.280 --> 00:42:17.750
Still nervous beforehand,
still sweating, but got better

00:42:17.750 --> 00:42:20.550
about managing it, and I knew
like the ultimate fear was

00:42:20.550 --> 00:42:24.045
gone, like me to stand there
and be like, what do I do?

00:42:24.045 --> 00:42:25.920
All of sudden you get
a lot more comfortable.

00:42:25.920 --> 00:42:28.050
There were loads of little
tips like that along the way

00:42:28.050 --> 00:42:30.110
that I was getting from
performers and comedians

00:42:30.110 --> 00:42:33.280
that I'd never, ever seen
in the world of business.

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:35.872
Any other kind of
wacky questions?

00:42:35.872 --> 00:42:37.580
AUDIENCE: You did that
by drawing it out?

00:42:37.580 --> 00:42:38.490
DAVID NIHILL: Yeah, definitely.

00:42:38.490 --> 00:42:40.290
AUDIENCE: Or you picturing
yourself in the space?

00:42:40.290 --> 00:42:42.123
DAVID NIHILL: I draw
it out just to help me.

00:42:42.123 --> 00:42:44.240
But I literally sit down
and visualize myself

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:45.560
walking through the house.

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:47.960
And the crazier the
stories I concoct, kind of

00:42:47.960 --> 00:42:50.920
like the bear in the taxi cab
and give it the extra detail,

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:52.770
who's the person,
put some celebrities

00:42:52.770 --> 00:42:55.570
in there, anything, the
crazier that story becomes

00:42:55.570 --> 00:42:57.740
that you create for
each bullet point,

00:42:57.740 --> 00:43:00.140
and then I just draw it out,
just as literally something

00:43:00.140 --> 00:43:01.840
to visualize that morning.

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:04.400
And to be honest, once maybe
I'll run through the talk

00:43:04.400 --> 00:43:05.320
in fast forward.

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:07.420
And if I can't say
the word really fast,

00:43:07.420 --> 00:43:08.957
I definitely can
say it really slow.

00:43:08.957 --> 00:43:11.040
It was a really good thing
that someone taught me.

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:13.414
Like when you put a quote in
a presentation, you're like,

00:43:13.414 --> 00:43:14.677
now I'd like to share a quote.

00:43:14.677 --> 00:43:16.260
And you're like, I
can't even remember

00:43:16.260 --> 00:43:18.570
what the quote is because
it's not as familiar as you

00:43:18.570 --> 00:43:20.220
thought it would be to you.

00:43:20.220 --> 00:43:21.720
And you can't say
it really fast.

00:43:21.720 --> 00:43:23.170
If you can't say it fast,
you can't say it slow.

00:43:23.170 --> 00:43:25.545
I think that was one of the
better tips somebody gave me.

00:43:25.545 --> 00:43:27.480
Someone also said
along the way, you

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:30.612
know, filler words-- Irish
people are great for mumbling,

00:43:30.612 --> 00:43:32.320
no offense Irish people
who are watching,

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:33.360
but we definitely do it.

00:43:33.360 --> 00:43:35.068
And it's why I have
a hard time sometimes

00:43:35.068 --> 00:43:37.762
with foreign languages of
sounding like a native speaker

00:43:37.762 --> 00:43:38.720
when I'm studying them.

00:43:38.720 --> 00:43:42.980
But the filler words that you
use, like uhh, eh, but-- anyone

00:43:42.980 --> 00:43:45.812
ever have problems with that
when you're public speaking?

00:43:45.812 --> 00:43:47.270
You watch it back,
and you're like,

00:43:47.270 --> 00:43:48.940
oh, I said eh so many times.

00:43:48.940 --> 00:43:52.260
But if you speak
literally like I am now,

00:43:52.260 --> 00:43:57.280
10% to 15% higher than normal,
it sounds totally normal to you

00:43:57.280 --> 00:43:57.970
guys.

00:43:57.970 --> 00:43:59.430
I feel like a lunatic.

00:43:59.430 --> 00:44:00.930
But it looks really,
really natural.

00:44:00.930 --> 00:44:02.013
And you know what happens?

00:44:02.013 --> 00:44:06.050
It's nearly impossible
to say uhh really loudly.

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:07.330
You just don't.

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:08.810
And all of a sudden,
the words come

00:44:08.810 --> 00:44:10.940
slower because you're
talking faster,

00:44:10.940 --> 00:44:13.150
and there isn't a
single filler word.

00:44:13.150 --> 00:44:15.820
And you've just cured that
problem as well straight away.

00:44:15.820 --> 00:44:17.380
I got that from
comedians as well.

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:18.754
All these little
things they were

00:44:18.754 --> 00:44:20.630
doing, that I was
thinking business speakers

00:44:20.630 --> 00:44:21.690
had never heard of.

00:44:21.690 --> 00:44:23.450
Like coming out to
a crowd and just get

00:44:23.450 --> 00:44:24.810
them to applaud for anything.

00:44:24.810 --> 00:44:26.310
Have you ever been
in a comedy club,

00:44:26.310 --> 00:44:28.686
and they're like, give it up
for your bar and wait staff!

00:44:28.686 --> 00:44:30.185
And you're like,
they're charging me

00:44:30.185 --> 00:44:31.330
so much money for drinks.

00:44:31.330 --> 00:44:32.610
They don't even come.

00:44:32.610 --> 00:44:35.210
And then when the comedian tries
to talk, they talk over them.

00:44:35.210 --> 00:44:36.810
I don't want to
applaud for them.

00:44:36.810 --> 00:44:37.684
But you do.

00:44:37.684 --> 00:44:39.350
Give it up for
yourselves for coming out

00:44:39.350 --> 00:44:40.930
to support live comedy tonight.

00:44:40.930 --> 00:44:41.744
Sound familiar?

00:44:41.744 --> 00:44:44.410
Now give it up for all the great
comedians you're about to hear.

00:44:44.410 --> 00:44:47.430
The rule of three, the same
law that applies to copywriting

00:44:47.430 --> 00:44:48.940
applies to your behavior.

00:44:48.940 --> 00:44:50.900
If you do something
three times like clap,

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:53.650
you're more likely to do
it again later in the show.

00:44:53.650 --> 00:44:56.180
So if they walk out, and it's
a totally flat audience, what

00:44:56.180 --> 00:44:57.890
they do is just ask them
for a round of applause.

00:44:57.890 --> 00:44:59.380
Just get them to do something.

00:44:59.380 --> 00:45:01.257
Comedians, again,
amazing at doing it.

00:45:01.257 --> 00:45:03.340
Introductions, when you're
introducing a speaker--

00:45:03.340 --> 00:45:04.841
and that was his
point-- do you ever

00:45:04.841 --> 00:45:07.006
have someone seen him coming
to a stage and be like,

00:45:07.006 --> 00:45:08.270
John is a friend of mine.

00:45:08.270 --> 00:45:09.740
John's our next speaker.

00:45:09.740 --> 00:45:12.120
He was an early stage
investor in his company.

00:45:12.120 --> 00:45:14.350
And every time he says the
word John, you're like,

00:45:14.350 --> 00:45:15.200
do we applaud now?

00:45:15.200 --> 00:45:15.810
No, OK.

00:45:15.810 --> 00:45:16.690
Said the name again.

00:45:16.690 --> 00:45:17.550
Do we applaud now?

00:45:17.550 --> 00:45:18.050
No.

00:45:18.050 --> 00:45:20.470
But comedy club-- ladies and
gentlemen, our next comedian

00:45:20.470 --> 00:45:21.610
has been on at the Punchline.

00:45:21.610 --> 00:45:22.480
You've seen him on the improv.

00:45:22.480 --> 00:45:23.900
You've seen him
on Comedy Central.

00:45:23.900 --> 00:45:24.680
He's huge.

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:26.790
Please give it up for,
and you as the audience

00:45:26.790 --> 00:45:28.315
are like, [GASPS] who is it?

00:45:28.315 --> 00:45:29.940
That's the only thing
you want to know.

00:45:29.940 --> 00:45:32.990
The anticipation is building
to what's now the punchline.

00:45:32.990 --> 00:45:34.450
It's the same structure.

00:45:34.450 --> 00:45:36.320
And when I say that
guy's name, now he

00:45:36.320 --> 00:45:39.060
gets a big round of applause
all of a sudden, in unison,

00:45:39.060 --> 00:45:40.560
from everybody at the same time.

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:43.170
Small little things like
that have a huge impact

00:45:43.170 --> 00:45:44.310
on what's going to happen.

00:45:44.310 --> 00:45:45.625
I saw a question from yourself.

00:45:45.625 --> 00:45:47.750
Was it, all the way-- did
you have one still or no?

00:45:47.750 --> 00:45:48.930
Finito.

00:45:48.930 --> 00:45:51.221
Yeah, same as don't end on
the questions and answers.

00:45:51.221 --> 00:45:52.220
Have you ever seen that?

00:45:52.220 --> 00:45:54.761
Or anyone do a Q&amp;A session where
you're literally standing up

00:45:54.761 --> 00:45:56.900
there, and the guy
comes back, the host,

00:45:56.900 --> 00:45:58.930
similar although he's
doing it much better.

00:45:58.930 --> 00:46:01.670
And it's literally like,
anyone got any questions?

00:46:01.670 --> 00:46:02.300
Nobody?

00:46:02.300 --> 00:46:03.470
And you're just standing
there as the speaker

00:46:03.470 --> 00:46:04.178
going, oh my god.

00:46:04.178 --> 00:46:06.479
I hope somebody asks a question
at some stage now soon.

00:46:06.479 --> 00:46:09.020
And then he'll be like, oh, guy
in the back, like I just did.

00:46:09.020 --> 00:46:10.560
And the guy's like,
no, wasn't me.

00:46:10.560 --> 00:46:13.310
It's gone, straight away, no
intention of asking a question,

00:46:13.310 --> 00:46:14.410
don't want to.

00:46:14.410 --> 00:46:17.240
And then the speaker, they kind
of go off stage like this, OK,

00:46:17.240 --> 00:46:18.070
thanks.

00:46:18.070 --> 00:46:18.860
Bye-bye.

00:46:18.860 --> 00:46:20.360
And the conference
organizer now has

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:22.010
to go back in and try
and edit that video

00:46:22.010 --> 00:46:23.718
and make it look like
they didn't go away

00:46:23.718 --> 00:46:25.760
on the flattest note in history.

00:46:25.760 --> 00:46:27.564
So literally, you
can change all that.

00:46:27.564 --> 00:46:29.230
A comedian would never
go out like that.

00:46:29.230 --> 00:46:31.850
It's Steve Jobs strong
ending for a comedian.

00:46:31.850 --> 00:46:33.740
Second strongest
joke at the start,

00:46:33.740 --> 00:46:36.560
strongest joke at the finish,
out with a bang-- everybody

00:46:36.560 --> 00:46:37.610
knows it's over.

00:46:37.610 --> 00:46:39.490
And as a business speaker,
all you have to do

00:46:39.490 --> 00:46:41.810
is say I'm going to take a
few questions and answers

00:46:41.810 --> 00:46:44.190
before making my conclusion.

00:46:44.190 --> 00:46:46.440
And if nobody asks a
question, who cares?

00:46:46.440 --> 00:46:48.290
I still have a
slide, which is going

00:46:48.290 --> 00:46:51.230
to have how many takeaways on it
that you're going to remember?

00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:51.870
Three.

00:46:51.870 --> 00:46:53.590
Still cannot
pronounce that word,

00:46:53.590 --> 00:46:56.880
but now I control the ending.

00:46:56.880 --> 00:46:58.802
So all of a sudden, I
know it's going to end.

00:46:58.802 --> 00:47:00.260
All of a sudden
you know it's over.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:02.840
All of a sudden the host
can say, round of applause.

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:03.750
You guys give it.

00:47:03.750 --> 00:47:04.710
Everybody's happy.

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:06.206
Makes a massive difference.

00:47:06.206 --> 00:47:07.580
Next time you go
to a conference,

00:47:07.580 --> 00:47:08.350
you're going to see that.

00:47:08.350 --> 00:47:09.570
They're going to be
running around with a mic.

00:47:09.570 --> 00:47:11.120
Nobody's saying
anything to speakers,

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:13.812
just standing there on stage
looking totally mortified.

00:47:13.812 --> 00:47:15.270
And because you
can't control that,

00:47:15.270 --> 00:47:16.853
you're leaving it
up to random chance.

00:47:16.853 --> 00:47:18.864
So good, good tip as well.

00:47:18.864 --> 00:47:21.370
Anything else?

00:47:21.370 --> 00:47:22.030
Yeah?

00:47:22.030 --> 00:47:22.530
Please.

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:26.159
We'll get you a microphone,
just so they can all hear it.

00:47:26.159 --> 00:47:28.450
I better turn off my little
potato picture [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:28.450 --> 00:47:30.285
AUDIENCE: Thank you for
coming to talk to us today.

00:47:30.285 --> 00:47:30.770
DAVID NIHILL: Oh, thank you.

00:47:30.770 --> 00:47:32.750
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering how long

00:47:32.750 --> 00:47:36.890
it took you to stop
feeling nervous on stage.

00:47:36.890 --> 00:47:39.052
You said you did
this for like a year?

00:47:39.052 --> 00:47:40.760
DAVID NIHILL: Yeah,
more than a year now.

00:47:40.760 --> 00:47:41.826
Never.

00:47:41.826 --> 00:47:43.700
And I wish someone had
told me that to start.

00:47:43.700 --> 00:47:45.850
I was like, when
does it get good?

00:47:45.850 --> 00:47:46.630
No.

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:48.650
And I'd go do
these comedy shows,

00:47:48.650 --> 00:47:51.250
and you'd think a green room
backstage to a comedy show,

00:47:51.250 --> 00:47:53.100
like 10 comedians are
in there, must be so

00:47:53.100 --> 00:47:55.980
fun in there-- not
fun whatsoever.

00:47:55.980 --> 00:47:56.480
Never.

00:47:56.480 --> 00:47:57.610
Everyone's super nervous.

00:47:57.610 --> 00:47:58.400
Like, they're getting ready.

00:47:58.400 --> 00:48:00.191
They're doing their
own way of preparation.

00:48:00.191 --> 00:48:03.160
They're still sweating and
shaking a lot of the time.

00:48:03.160 --> 00:48:05.160
If there's consequences,
you're always nervous.

00:48:05.160 --> 00:48:08.440
And it was just reframing
that to say, I'm not nervous.

00:48:08.440 --> 00:48:09.159
I'm excited.

00:48:09.159 --> 00:48:10.200
And this is what happens.

00:48:10.200 --> 00:48:12.640
Nobody's trying to kill me
on a daily basis anymore,

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:15.940
so that fight or flight
moment doesn't really happen.

00:48:15.940 --> 00:48:18.110
It happens with little
things like public speaking,

00:48:18.110 --> 00:48:19.690
or it happens with
like a road rage

00:48:19.690 --> 00:48:21.400
incident that leads to nothing.

00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:23.320
It's non-threatening
things where we get that,

00:48:23.320 --> 00:48:24.903
and you do get it
for public speaking.

00:48:24.903 --> 00:48:25.904
And it doesn't go away.

00:48:25.904 --> 00:48:26.820
It becomes manageable.

00:48:26.820 --> 00:48:30.070
But reframing that in your head,
that makes all the difference.

00:48:30.070 --> 00:48:31.320
You're like, oh, I'm sweating.

00:48:31.320 --> 00:48:32.153
This always happens.

00:48:32.153 --> 00:48:33.381
OK, I'm perfectly prepared.

00:48:33.381 --> 00:48:35.130
So if you get it in
your head like, right.

00:48:35.130 --> 00:48:37.910
If I was an IndyCar race car
driver, and I'm in the final,

00:48:37.910 --> 00:48:39.910
and it's a championship
decider, would it

00:48:39.910 --> 00:48:42.110
be a good idea if I
took a shot of vodka

00:48:42.110 --> 00:48:44.250
just before I drove the
car, a shot of tequila,

00:48:44.250 --> 00:48:45.206
to null the senses?

00:48:45.206 --> 00:48:46.080
It would be terrible.

00:48:46.080 --> 00:48:47.570
Public speaking is the same.

00:48:47.570 --> 00:48:49.127
Like if something
happens in a room,

00:48:49.127 --> 00:48:50.710
you want to react
to it straight away.

00:48:50.710 --> 00:48:52.617
And you're at your
most heightened state.

00:48:52.617 --> 00:48:54.950
That's your best condition,
when the heartbeat is going.

00:48:54.950 --> 00:48:57.177
But you do little things
like wear clothing you know

00:48:57.177 --> 00:48:59.010
is kind of sweat proof
so it doesn't show it

00:48:59.010 --> 00:49:00.109
if you're getting sweaty.

00:49:00.109 --> 00:49:01.650
If there's a microphone
in the stand,

00:49:01.650 --> 00:49:03.830
I would never take it out
for the first 30 seconds,

00:49:03.830 --> 00:49:05.881
because I know I'm going
to be shaking so much.

00:49:05.881 --> 00:49:07.380
But the nice thing
is if I'm relying

00:49:07.380 --> 00:49:09.800
on my stories and
my content, that's

00:49:09.800 --> 00:49:13.140
what I'm using in my talk,
and I start with a story,

00:49:13.140 --> 00:49:14.490
then I'm not going to forget it.

00:49:14.490 --> 00:49:15.080
It's mine.

00:49:15.080 --> 00:49:17.150
And if I mess it up,
you don't know anyway.

00:49:17.150 --> 00:49:18.970
So I get way more
comfortable about what

00:49:18.970 --> 00:49:20.047
I'm about to talk about.

00:49:20.047 --> 00:49:21.630
And if I have all
that stuff memorized

00:49:21.630 --> 00:49:22.470
that we were talking
about earlier,

00:49:22.470 --> 00:49:25.230
and I know the logical sequence,
and I know I have one or two

00:49:25.230 --> 00:49:28.130
things that will 100%
get people to laugh,

00:49:28.130 --> 00:49:29.651
or I know I can
just show a video,

00:49:29.651 --> 00:49:31.400
and the video is going
to make them laugh,

00:49:31.400 --> 00:49:33.840
or a couple of memes, and
you get really comfortable

00:49:33.840 --> 00:49:34.486
pretty quick.

00:49:34.486 --> 00:49:36.860
So to answer your question,
you know, it never goes away.

00:49:36.860 --> 00:49:38.750
And I wish people just
said that all the time

00:49:38.750 --> 00:49:39.541
and admitted to it.

00:49:39.541 --> 00:49:43.000
But if you reframe it, then it
gets pretty easy to deal with.

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:45.000
So one more question
if we have one,

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:47.570
otherwise I'll
just finish it up.

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:48.407
Yeah?

00:49:48.407 --> 00:49:50.240
AUDIENCE: I was just
wondering your thoughts

00:49:50.240 --> 00:49:52.564
about the choice of a story.

00:49:52.564 --> 00:49:53.980
If you're talking
about something,

00:49:53.980 --> 00:49:55.810
it's not exactly public.

00:49:55.810 --> 00:49:59.900
But we have a lot of things that
are like [INAUDIBLE] 10 people.

00:49:59.900 --> 00:50:03.900
How you're designing this
component of a software system,

00:50:03.900 --> 00:50:06.930
or how you're marketing--
some in between.

00:50:06.930 --> 00:50:08.562
You'd never do a TED Talk.

00:50:08.562 --> 00:50:09.770
DAVID NIHILL: No, true, true.

00:50:09.770 --> 00:50:12.250
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:12.250 --> 00:50:14.410
But you don't tell a story
about your childhood.

00:50:14.410 --> 00:50:15.970
It has no relation whatsoever.

00:50:15.970 --> 00:50:16.470
So--

00:50:16.470 --> 00:50:18.270
DAVID NIHILL: Well, I
mean, sometimes it does.

00:50:18.270 --> 00:50:20.090
But I mean, that's kind
of a different form

00:50:20.090 --> 00:50:21.140
because it's a
bit more personal.

00:50:21.140 --> 00:50:22.790
There's five or 10
of you in the room.

00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:24.760
But why are you
making this change?

00:50:24.760 --> 00:50:26.670
So there was a really
good example at Skype

00:50:26.670 --> 00:50:29.800
when they launched the
video conferencing component

00:50:29.800 --> 00:50:30.300
to Skype.

00:50:30.300 --> 00:50:31.590
Most of the staff
were against it.

00:50:31.590 --> 00:50:33.460
They're like, that's
not our core component.

00:50:33.460 --> 00:50:35.990
So the CEO brought into
their weekly meetings

00:50:35.990 --> 00:50:38.380
they were doing at the time
customers who were literally

00:50:38.380 --> 00:50:39.713
the people that were using this.

00:50:39.713 --> 00:50:41.660
And the guy'd come in,
and he's like, listen,

00:50:41.660 --> 00:50:43.271
I was in the military
for six months.

00:50:43.271 --> 00:50:45.270
And the only way I kept
my relationship together

00:50:45.270 --> 00:50:48.270
with my wife was by using the
video technology component.

00:50:48.270 --> 00:50:50.360
We have to roll out this beta.

00:50:50.360 --> 00:50:53.040
So if you weren't able to tell
the story of the user's problem

00:50:53.040 --> 00:50:54.500
you were trying to
solve, they were actually

00:50:54.500 --> 00:50:56.590
bringing in these people
and [INAUDIBLE] them.

00:50:56.590 --> 00:50:59.429
So I think you just
vocalize who is the end user

00:50:59.429 --> 00:51:00.720
that your problem is affecting.

00:51:00.720 --> 00:51:02.760
Where you guys, you
always have an end user.

00:51:02.760 --> 00:51:06.920
So your opinion is not as strong
a way of motivating people

00:51:06.920 --> 00:51:08.225
as the story.

00:51:08.225 --> 00:51:09.600
Why does it affect
those persons?

00:51:09.600 --> 00:51:12.490
What was the frustration in it
for them if we don't fix this?

00:51:12.490 --> 00:51:13.400
Vocalize that.

00:51:13.400 --> 00:51:15.461
Now hit them with
a few solutions.

00:51:15.461 --> 00:51:15.960
Yeah.

00:51:15.960 --> 00:51:17.390
It tends to work.

00:51:17.390 --> 00:51:20.020
Yeah, I better tell you guys the
end of all this lunacy for me.

00:51:20.020 --> 00:51:22.270
And the nice thing for it,
remember this sign earlier?

00:51:22.270 --> 00:51:23.960
The sequence of three.

00:51:23.960 --> 00:51:24.860
This is rubbish.

00:51:24.860 --> 00:51:27.300
You can nearly feel the
frustration in this sign

00:51:27.300 --> 00:51:27.980
as you read it.

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:30.660
You're like, I've tried
comedy, but it's not working.

00:51:30.660 --> 00:51:31.160
All right.

00:51:31.160 --> 00:51:32.190
Roses are red.

00:51:32.190 --> 00:51:33.050
Bacon is red.

00:51:33.050 --> 00:51:35.125
Poems are hard-- bacon.

00:51:35.125 --> 00:51:37.700
It's exactly like they just
gave up on the process,

00:51:37.700 --> 00:51:40.210
but it's still kind
of funny, right?

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:43.394
If you try to be funny ever,
and it doesn't get a laugh,

00:51:43.394 --> 00:51:45.310
all you have to do is
acknowledge how terrible

00:51:45.310 --> 00:51:47.410
it was and everybody's cool.

00:51:47.410 --> 00:51:49.540
It's that guy who thinks
he's amazing at public

00:51:49.540 --> 00:51:51.706
speaking or doing something
in front of an audience.

00:51:51.706 --> 00:51:53.325
And you're like, well, he sucks.

00:51:53.325 --> 00:51:54.700
That's when you're
not liking it.

00:51:54.700 --> 00:51:56.790
But as long as they're like,
that would joke was terrible,

00:51:56.790 --> 00:51:57.220
wasn't it?

00:51:57.220 --> 00:51:58.300
I'll never try that again.

00:51:58.300 --> 00:51:58.720
OK.

00:51:58.720 --> 00:51:59.010
Good.

00:51:59.010 --> 00:51:59.670
We'll remember that.

00:51:59.670 --> 00:52:01.086
It was funny last
night when I was

00:52:01.086 --> 00:52:03.900
practicing my cat-- did not
translate to the main stage

00:52:03.900 --> 00:52:04.400
today.

00:52:04.400 --> 00:52:04.900
Cool.

00:52:04.900 --> 00:52:07.490
Then everybody's
still happy with it.

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:09.730
I mean, the nice thing
behind it, I love this metric

00:52:09.730 --> 00:52:12.146
and I love the little cute
baby photo, obviously, as well.

00:52:12.146 --> 00:52:15.700
But we used to laugh
300 times a day,

00:52:15.700 --> 00:52:18.250
and now they reckon
it's somewhere about 15,

00:52:18.250 --> 00:52:20.400
depending on the age
bracket, 15 to 20.

00:52:20.400 --> 00:52:22.990
So like anybody who can stick
in a little bit of laughter

00:52:22.990 --> 00:52:25.190
there quickly becomes
a bit of a hero.

00:52:25.190 --> 00:52:26.790
And like the average
conference, it's

00:52:26.790 --> 00:52:28.360
not the most difficult audience.

00:52:28.360 --> 00:52:30.950
The average conference
speaker is horrendous.

00:52:30.950 --> 00:52:33.339
They're literally like a
group of happy dolphins

00:52:33.339 --> 00:52:35.005
when you bring in
humor going backwards.

00:52:35.005 --> 00:52:37.100
They're like, oh,
that was so great.

00:52:37.100 --> 00:52:39.855
My day just got much better.

00:52:39.855 --> 00:52:41.230
That was a book
I wrote about it,

00:52:41.230 --> 00:52:43.709
and there's loads of tips in
there, huge amount of tips.

00:52:43.709 --> 00:52:46.000
But if you don't want to buy
it, you can get those tips

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:49.490
for free, totally, just by going
to 7comedyhabits.com/80tips

00:52:49.490 --> 00:52:50.760
and download them all.

00:52:50.760 --> 00:52:52.919
So I'm not writing this
book to write 10 books

00:52:52.919 --> 00:52:54.543
or become an expert
on public speaking.

00:52:54.543 --> 00:52:56.410
I hate public speaking.

00:52:56.410 --> 00:52:59.250
It took a lot of arm twisting
even to get me on video

00:52:59.250 --> 00:53:01.069
and doing this one
and coming today.

00:53:01.069 --> 00:53:03.110
Because I really don't
like to be a video either.

00:53:03.110 --> 00:53:04.250
So I still hate public speaking.

00:53:04.250 --> 00:53:05.958
I don't want to be
going around doing it.

00:53:05.958 --> 00:53:07.937
But if you want to get
in touch, that's me.

00:53:07.937 --> 00:53:09.270
I'll put that up again in a sec.

00:53:09.270 --> 00:53:10.728
I didn't want to
leave you hanging.

00:53:10.728 --> 00:53:13.060
Remember this story I
was done for 1,400 people

00:53:13.060 --> 00:53:14.995
and nearly laying
an egg on stage?

00:53:14.995 --> 00:53:16.370
And I was trying
to tell you guys

00:53:16.370 --> 00:53:18.430
you never know what will happen
when you tell your story.

00:53:18.430 --> 00:53:20.013
So that was pretty
much the conclusion

00:53:20.013 --> 00:53:21.860
of my public
speaking experiments.

00:53:21.860 --> 00:53:23.960
I did this big
storytelling competition,

00:53:23.960 --> 00:53:25.506
and I went early
on in the night.

00:53:25.506 --> 00:53:26.630
There were 10 storytellers.

00:53:26.630 --> 00:53:29.404
And I was winning all
the way right to the end.

00:53:29.404 --> 00:53:31.320
And my friends were like,
you're going to win!

00:53:31.320 --> 00:53:33.528
And I was thinking it would
be a good end to the book

00:53:33.528 --> 00:53:34.420
this one if I win.

00:53:34.420 --> 00:53:36.640
And then the very last
lady went and won,

00:53:36.640 --> 00:53:38.770
beat me like point
point something.

00:53:38.770 --> 00:53:39.980
And I was like, aw.

00:53:39.980 --> 00:53:41.700
There goes the happy ending.

00:53:41.700 --> 00:53:44.210
And then two weeks later,
this guy contacted me.

00:53:44.210 --> 00:53:47.290
And that was a manager of a very
famous comedian but was also

00:53:47.290 --> 00:53:51.220
the producer of TEDx Marin,
one of the bigger high profile

00:53:51.220 --> 00:53:52.020
events here.

00:53:52.020 --> 00:53:53.519
And he's like, hey,
David, would you

00:53:53.519 --> 00:53:56.300
like to come and tell a story
or do a talk at our TED event?

00:53:56.300 --> 00:53:58.720
And I was thinking, that's
quite a twist for somebody who

00:53:58.720 --> 00:53:59.270
hated public speaking.

00:53:59.270 --> 00:54:00.360
That's pretty cool, actually.

00:54:00.360 --> 00:54:01.818
And then before I
got carried away,

00:54:01.818 --> 00:54:03.400
I was like, oh, wait a minute.

00:54:03.400 --> 00:54:06.140
I have a friend,
and he's the reason

00:54:06.140 --> 00:54:08.770
I got into all this stuff
when he suffered a spinal cord

00:54:08.770 --> 00:54:09.460
injury.

00:54:09.460 --> 00:54:12.080
And he just did a talk,
and I helped him craft it.

00:54:12.080 --> 00:54:13.110
And he gave it.

00:54:13.110 --> 00:54:16.260
And he went on after Guy
Kawasaki, like his first talk

00:54:16.260 --> 00:54:17.740
ever, and crushed it.

00:54:17.740 --> 00:54:20.350
And his second talk ever, he
used the techniques I used,

00:54:20.350 --> 00:54:22.310
the memory palace there
that I taught him,

00:54:22.310 --> 00:54:24.660
and he got written up
in Forbes about it.

00:54:24.660 --> 00:54:26.410
And I was like, let
me send you his video.

00:54:26.410 --> 00:54:27.140
I think you'll like it.

00:54:27.140 --> 00:54:28.760
And the guy watched it,
and he wrote back to me.

00:54:28.760 --> 00:54:29.571
He's like, awesome.

00:54:29.571 --> 00:54:30.070
Booked.

00:54:30.070 --> 00:54:30.690
Done.

00:54:30.690 --> 00:54:32.190
If you don't mind,
we'll put him on.

00:54:32.190 --> 00:54:32.990
I was like, no, man.

00:54:32.990 --> 00:54:33.490
Put him on.

00:54:33.490 --> 00:54:34.650
That's going to be epic.

00:54:34.650 --> 00:54:35.540
So he went.

00:54:35.540 --> 00:54:37.370
He gave that TED Talk.

00:54:37.370 --> 00:54:38.880
That's me and him
on stage at it.

00:54:38.880 --> 00:54:40.090
I was watching backstage.

00:54:40.090 --> 00:54:41.490
He was the very last speaker.

00:54:41.490 --> 00:54:44.490
